You guys remember these books? Pulpy, paperback romance novels that you could find a dime-a-dozen at any book or even grocery store? If you don't, they're basically an extremely cheesy (kind of so-bad-they're-good) form of stories that delve heavily into female wish fulfillment. The subject of these stories is usually an average woman who is bored, dissatisfied, or going through something difficult in her life when she suddenly meets an incredibly handsome man who inexplicably begins taking interest in her. They flirt, he pursues her, they get together, usually ends happily. It's the kind of stuff your mom might read.

But imagine this: one of these books, but HMOFA. We see the same story play out from the perspective of an anthro girl. She's bored with her life and everything around her... until she suddenly meets a buff human stud who immediately begins flirting with her. She falls for him immediately and longs for him to whisk her away to an enormous mansion in the countryside. (She assumes he's rich, let's just say he is) Eventually, she overcomes the disapproval of her parents/siblings/community/etc. and runs off with the human to live happily ever after. And, of course, the cover for this novel is just as steamy as the one I posted, but with an anthro girl in place of the human one.

Would you read this book?

How about this, but one of those Hallmark TV Christmas specials? You know the kind, a woman who has a swanky city job in the humanities (writing, artist, fashion designer, etc..) who is coming back to their small hometown for christmas for the first time in several years. The reasoning behind their not going back in several years undoubtedly tied to something tragic, but common, such as the death of a family member, most likely a parent. The first 10 minutes has her emerging from an airport terminal/train station to be greeted by a family member or old friend, and then walking through a town square that we'll see another half dozen times before the movie's over, while squeezing as much expository dialogue between them regarding herself, the town, and the christmas event the city is planning that will serve as a romantic setpeice later on. At home she'll be greeted by surviving family and ONE cute precocious kid who will somehow be pivitol in her either meeting, falling in love with, or overcoming the act 3 misunderstanding with the male lead. The male lead will inevitably be an acclaimed architect/author/musician with a smart turtleneck below a strong jawline. The informaiton established to this point then writing itself until these two meet, discover that they are the same character, and fall for each other as intended until an old flame of his shows up and forces themselves on him to fuel the act 3 misunderstanding where our heroine angrily pouts about men being all the same. Soon the male lead is exonerated, and the two walk happily hand in hand in the snow covered town square, while the camera pulls out slowly to the swelling sounds of Vanessa Carlton's piano.

Would you watch it if it were hmofa?
